<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-100-634  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 100 634.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  March 6 1989 v11 n10 p66(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fast and slim, the Ultralite is a leap forward in laptops.andO;(column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Miller, Michael J.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>NEC Home Electronics (U.S.A) Inc's Ultralite laptop computer($2,999 to $3,699) is slim, light and fast, and has an excellentscreen and keyboard.andP;  The Ultralite also gives users microcomputercompatibility in a computer that fits in a briefcase and stillleaves room.andP;  Ultralite is powered by a 9.8-MHz NEC V30, comeswith 640Kbytes of RAM, but is about half the size and less thanhalf the weight of most other MS-DOS laptops.andP;  A unique feature ofUltralite is that it does not have a built-in disk drive, but usesa 1Mbyte or 2Mbyte 'silicon hard disk,' a battery-backed RAM disk,which lets applications load and run quickly.andP;  The laptop also hasa 2,400-bps built-in modem and a very nice backlit screen.andP;  Amajor disadvantage of Ultralite is its limited battery life, whichlasts only two hours and takes 16 hours for an initial charge, andfive to seven hours for subsequent charges.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   NEC Home Electronics (U.S.A.) Inc. (products).andO;Product:   NEC Ultralite (Portable computer).andO;Topic:     EvaluationLaptop ComputersPower Supply.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>